/**
 * In-memory collection of Kafka record batches backed by a ByteBuffer.
 *
 * <p><strong>Purpose:</strong>
 * This class manages a contiguous buffer containing one or more {@link RecordBatch} objects,
 * providing iteration, filtering, slicing, and serialization capabilities. It is used throughout
 * Kafka for handling batches in producers, consumers, brokers, and administrative operations.
 *
 * <p><strong>Use Cases:</strong>
 * <ul>
 *   <li><strong>Reading Existing Batches:</strong> Use {@link #readableRecords(ByteBuffer)} to wrap
 *       an existing buffer for reading.</li>
 *   <li><strong>Creating New Batches:</strong> Use {@link #builder(ByteBuffer, Compression, TimestampType, long)}
 *       or {@link MemoryRecordsBuilder} for batch construction.</li>
 *   <li><strong>Log Filtering & Compaction:</strong> Use {@link #filterTo(RecordFilter, ByteBuffer, BufferSupplier)}
 *       to filter records by retention policy during log compaction.</li>
 *   <li><strong>Network I/O:</strong> Use {@link #writeTo(java.nio.channels.GatheringByteChannel)} or
 *       {@link #writeTo(java.nio.channels.TransferableChannel, int, int)} for efficient data transmission.</li>
 * </ul>
 *
 * <p><strong>Batch Structure:</strong>
 * The buffer contains a sequence of batches (one or more). Each batch encapsulates records with shared
 * metadata (compression type, timestamp type, producer ID, etc.). Batches are decoded lazily as they are
 * iterated; use {@link #batches()} to iterate over all batches or individual methods like
 * {@link #firstBatchSize()} to inspect specific batches.
 *
 * <p><strong>Decompression & Iterator Semantics:</strong>
 * <ul>
 *   <li><strong>Streaming Iteration:</strong> {@link RecordBatch#streamingIterator(BufferSupplier)}
 *       defers decompression until records are consumed, reducing memory footprint.</li>
 *   <li><strong>Regular Iteration:</strong> {@link RecordBatch#iterator()} decompresses the full batch
 *       upfront, allowing iteration without resource management concerns.</li>
 *   <li><strong>Filtering:</strong> {@link #filterTo(RecordFilter, ByteBuffer, BufferSupplier)} combines
 *       batch and record filtering, supporting log compaction and retention policies.</li>
 * </ul>
 *
 * <p><strong>Thread Safety:</strong>
 * This class is NOT thread-safe. The underlying ByteBuffer is accessed without synchronization.
 * Multiple threads must not read or write the same MemoryRecords instance concurrently.
 * For concurrent access, wrap each thread's iteration with external synchronization or use
 * thread-local instances.
 *
 * <p><strong>Buffer Ownership & Lifecycle:</strong>
 * MemoryRecords does not own the backing ByteBuffer; the caller is responsible for:
 * <ul>
 *   <li>Keeping the buffer valid during MemoryRecords' lifetime</li>
 *   <li>Releasing/deallocating the buffer when no longer needed</li>
 *   <li>Avoiding modifications to the buffer while iteration is in progress</li>
 * </ul>
 *
 * <p><strong>Performance Characteristics:</strong>
 * <ul>
 *   <li><strong>Lazy Batch Parsing:</strong> Batches are decoded on-demand during iteration.</li>
 *   <li><strong>Valid Bytes Caching:</strong> {@link #validBytes()} is computed once and cached;
 *       invalidate by creating a new MemoryRecords instance if the buffer changes.</li>
 *   <li><strong>Decompression Buffers:</strong> Provide reusable {@link BufferSupplier} instances
 *       to streaming iterators to reduce allocations for large compressed batches.</li>
 * </ul>
 *
 * @see RecordBatch for the batch interface
 * @see MemoryRecordsBuilder for constructing new MemoryRecords
